New results of the Swedish asylum age screening tests published
The recent results of tests for asylum seekers in Sweden, which have undergone a new method of medical evaluation of their age, show that more than 80% of the people tested are older than 18 years, but not everyone believes in the accuracy of these results.
The Swedish Forensic Medicine Agency (Rättsmedicinalverket) began carrying out the tests last year.
They are to be more precise during the asylum procedure in assessing the age after the Swedish migration authority was criticised for errors in assessing the correct age of some refugees who were underage.
To date, migration has sent 6,880 cases to be tested, and the Forensic Medicine Agency has now published the results of a total of 2,481 tests from mid-March to July 31, 2017.
Eighty percent (2002) were judged as 18 or older, while in other 25 cases the Forensic Medicine Agency judged that the person "may have been 18 years or older".
In 432 cases, the conclusion was that the person "may be under 18 years old".
The tests are only carried out in cases where the age of the person is questioned.
According to Johan Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency, the results have been consistent in recent months.
"We do not see a big difference in the statistics of recent months, the numbers are quite constant," he said the magazine The Local.
The high proportion of cases in which the person has been judged over 18 years does not necessarily mean that the asylum seeker has lied about his age.
In May, the agency published the results of 581 tests and said that there were 442 cases that "propose that the investigated person be 18 years or older".
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet examined the 581 published results, she found that in 243 of these cases the person had openly said that she would be 18 years old this year.
The method of medical age assessment, in which X-rays were closely related to whiteness zones and MRT shots of knee joints, which are then analysed by dentists and radiologists, has also been criticised in some areas.
A skeptic is the endocrinologist Claude Marcus of the Karolinska Institute, whose work involves evaluating the biological maturity of humans to see if they used to go through puberty sooner or later.
"I had reason to think about this and I do not think that the type of measurement should be used.
The biological age to judge this way is very uncertain.
If we cannot say it safely, we should not pretend that we could "he said the newspaper Metro.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Medicine Agency defended the accuracy of the tests: "In general, you can say that the risk of judging a child as an adult is incorrect is small..
The biggest risk is if the person is just under 18, in this case this is about 10 percent. "
