Facebook wants to intensify fact-finding in the fight against counterfeit news
Facebook wants to send more potential articles to fact-checking auditors from third parties and then display their results under the original entry, said the world's largest online social network on Thursday.
The company said in an opinion on its website that it will start using updated machine learning methods to detect possible wrinkles and to send them to fact-checking auditors who may display the results of the fact-checking from the original article.
Facebook has been criticized as one of the main points of defense for so-called fake news, many of which believe that it has also affected the 2016 US presidential election.
The problem has also become a major political issue in Europe, with French voters being flooded with false stories in the run-up to the presidential elections in May, and Germany supporting a plan to penalise social media networks if they fail to eliminate hastily filled postings as they did before the elections there in September.
On Thursday, Facebook said in a separate statement in German that in the USA, France, the Netherlands and Germany a test of the new fact-checking will be launched.
"In addition to recognizing what stories are challenged by fake auditors of third parties, people want more context to make informed decisions about what they read and share," said Sara Su, product manager for Facebook news in a blog.
She added that Facebook will continue to test its feature to the "related article" and work on other changes to its news feed to reduce false messages.
