Afghan democracy depends on the political role of women, says the UN.
Elections can only be representative if all members of society, including women, play a role, said the head of the UN mission in Afghanistan on Wednesday.
Nicholas Haysom, acting head of the United Nations mission, said that hundreds of women will stand in provincial elections in the Council elections, with three women standing for the role of Vice-President and more than 30% of newly registered voters being women.
"The role of women can not be overestimated," he said on Wednesday in a statement.
Elections can only be truly representative and credible if women participate fully and are involved in all parts of the electoral process.
Afghan elections for the provincial council and presidential elections will take place on 5 April.
The Taliban have published threats against an electoral process that coincides with the transition from international fighting to an advisory role.
This year, for the first time, elections will hand over power peacefully from a democratically elected government to the next one.
Haysom said that a strong role for women will further strengthen Afghanistan's democratic success.
The Afghan Independent Electoral Commission reports that 1.2 million women are registered by a total of 3.6 million voters.
