GMB concerns about investment in the McVitie factory in Glasgow
A trade union wants to reassure McVitie, the Biskuit manufacturer, about the long-term commitment to production at its Glasgow plant.
GMB Scotland said the company has weighed over the future of investments at Tollcross-site.
More than 500 employees work at the plant, which besides other products produces hobbies and Rich Tea biscuits.
McVity ’ s owner, Pladis, said that he has invested more than £5 million in recent years.
He added that employees and trade union representatives would be "experienced first" if their activities changed.
In a letter to the company's chief executive, GMB Scotland McVitie's called for "expressing concern that funding for the modernisation of production lines will not be pushed forward".
GMB-Senior-Organisator Drew Duffy, said: "The fact that we can not gain clarity from the General-Site-Manager about the business needs and investment plans for the future of Tollcross concerns our members deeply.
Generations of families have worked here, and the workforce is focusing heavily on the local community and the Glasgow area, an important pillar of decent employment in an area of high unemployment and social deprivation.
Thus, from the perspective of jobs, wages, and prosperity, and against the backdrop of Brexit, rising cost of living, and chronic decline in output, the eastern end of Glasgow urgently needs a flourishing McVitie production presence. "
A spokesperson for Pladis said: "The head of the subsidiary at Tollcross received a letter from GMB Scotland only yesterday, and the company will respond directly to this, as we appreciate the continued commitment of employees and trade union representatives.
Two months ago we had a regular meeting with staff and GMB representatives at Tollcross, where some questions were discussed openly.
We discussed with the employees that we, like all companies operating in an extremely competitive and insecure economic climate, are constantly reviewing our business - and this applies to all our business areas and locations - in order to remain competitive.
She added: "In recent years, we have invested more than GBP 5 million in our Tollcross-site, particularly in production lines and operational improvements.
We recognize the heritage of Tollcross as a production site and we fully acknowledge that if our operations change at the site, employees and their trade union representatives will be the first to know this. "
